Model training and testing

6) Splitting the data into train and test set

# Get the index of the "charges" column
charges_index <- which(names(data) == "charges")

# Splitting the dataset into training and test sets 
set.seed(123)
train_index <- createDataPartition(new_data$charges, p=0.70, list=FALSE)
X_train <- new_data[train_index, -charges_index]
y_train <- new_data[train_index, charges_index]
X_test <- new_data[-train_index, -charges_index]
y_test <- new_data[-train_index, charges_index]

# delete indices in the dataframes 
row.names(X_train) <- NULL
row.names(X_test) <- NULL

# Normalize the data using Min-Max scaling
process <- preProcess(X_train, method='range')
X_train <- predict(process, X_train)
process <- preProcess(X_test, method='range')
X_test <- predict(process, X_test)

Regression tasks

Function to test the performance of a regression model

regression_test <- function(pred, y) {
  # Compute performance metrics
  rmse <- sqrt(mean((pred - y)^2))
  r2 <- cor(pred, y)^2
  mae <- mean(abs(pred - y))
  # Print the performance metrics
  print(paste("RMSE      :", rmse))
  print(paste("R-squared :", r2))
  print(paste("MAE       :", mae))
}

Function for the comparison of the predictions of a model and the true values on the testing data

performance_plot <- function(pred, y) {
  # Create the residuals data that contain the predictions values and the ground truth values for the plotting 
  residuals <- data.frame(
    predictions = pred,
    ground_truth = y
  )
  # plot 
  ggplot(residuals, aes(x = predictions, y = ground_truth)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, color = "red") +
    ggtitle("Predictions vs. True Values") +
    xlab("Predictions") +
    ylab("True Values")
}

random forest

# Fit the random forest model to the training set
model <- randomForest(y_train ~ ., data=X_train)
# Make predictions on the test set
predRanFor <- predict(model, X_test)
# Compute performance metrics
cat("Performance on Test data:\n")
## Performance on Test data:
regression_test(predRanFor, y_test)
## [1] "RMSE      : 5783.21024762581"
## [1] "R-squared : 0.763349262521374"
## [1] "MAE       : 3686.56827905945"
performance_plot(predRanFor, y_test)

residual <- y_test-predRanFor
plot(residual)

Hyperparameter tuning of the models

knn

cat("Performance on Train data:\n")
## Performance on Train data:
# Define the hyperparameter grid
grid <- expand.grid(k = c(1, 2, 3))
# Train the model using the train function with the tuneGrid argument
model <- train(x = X_train, y = y_train, method = 'knn', tuneGrid = grid, metric='RMSE', trControl = trainControl(method = 'cv', number = 5))
# Predict the train set using the best model
predictions <- predict(model, data = X_train)
# Compute performance metrics
regression_test(predictions, y_train)
## [1] "RMSE      : 4761.56844339744"
## [1] "R-squared : 0.848164939012562"
## [1] "MAE       : 2929.46535951792"
cat("\nPerformance on Test data:\n")
## 
## Performance on Test data:
# Testing on the test data
model <- train(x = X_test, y = y_test, method = 'knn', tuneGrid = NULL, metric='RMSE', trControl = trainControl(method = 'cv', number = 10))
# Predict the test set using the best model
predictions <- predict(model, data = X_test)
# Compute performance metrics
regression_test(predictions, y_test)
## [1] "RMSE      : 5614.8307326628"
## [1] "R-squared : 0.776724155698067"
## [1] "MAE       : 3687.64631424275"

plot(residual)
